choices.text:
definitely technology: iPhones, social media, etc. I never really wanted or needed an iPhone until my friends got them, which was only a few years ago. I can’t pinpoint when the change happened, but I think it was four or five years ago when social media as we know it today blew up. Now, we’re all (for the most part) glued to our phones, using them even for the smallest of things. It affects our mental health in the end. Valentina attended an all girls’ school and both her and her two sisters were subjected to cyber bullying, so she felt like her younger sister needed to be safer online. That might’ve been the first time when I started to use my phone differently, since she showed me how to use a parental control app which I might’ve mentioned before. It’s much safer now.

This week we discussed how technology affects happiness and mental health. When we were discussing this topic with Valentina, I understood her perspective on the small negativity that surrounds a lot of social media platforms like Instagram and Twitter. They’re focused on making their members happy and making sure their audience doesn’t suffer from any harm. If they fail at doing this, they get into a lot of trouble.
